The following Java code is intended to calculate the factorial of a given number. It has a potential overflow issue that could cause incorrect results for larger numbers.  Modify the code to handle potential overflow issues, preventing it from producing incorrect results for larger inputs.

```java
public class Factorial {
    public static long factorial(int n) {
        long result = 1;
        for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
            result *= i;
        }
        return result;
    }
}

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(factorial(5));
    }
}
```

reference:
The bug is that the result is a `long`, but the multiplication could still overflow.  The fix is to add a check for overflow before each multiplication.  

```java
public class Factorial {
    public static long factorial(int n) {
        long result = 1;
        for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
            if (result > Long.MAX_VALUE / i) { // Check for overflow
                return -1; // Or throw an exception, depending on requirements
            }
            result *= i;
        }
        return result;
    }
}

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(factorial(5));
    }
}
```

